                <head>363. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On Sunday, November 13, Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_DAW1"
                        >Dulles</persName> held a meeting on disarmament with his senior staff at 9
                    a.m. At 10, he and Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_MVM1"
                        >Molotov</persName> met at his office in the Palais des Nations to consider
                    United Nations membership, trade controls on China, the tanker <hi rend="italic"
                        >Tuapse</hi>, the future work of the conference, and the Middle East.
                    Following the meeting with <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName> had lunch with <persName
                        corresp="#p_MH1">Macmillan</persName>. In the evening, the Secretary and his
                    principal advisers discussed East-West contacts, and at 6:50 <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName> reviewed the disarmament question with
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">Stassen</persName>. (Department of State,
                    Conference Files: Lot 60 D 627, CF 584)</p>
                <p>A record of the meeting with <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>
                    follows. A brief memorandum of the lunch with <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Macmillan</persName> is <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>. No records have been
                    found for the other meetings in Department of State files.</p>
            </div>
